03267nam a22006015i 9780292753259DE-B159720211129102213.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||211129t20211999txu    fo  d z      eng d  a97802927532597 a10.7560/7121332doi  a(DE-B1597)588003  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  atxucUS-TX 7aLIT0000002bisacsh04a86300aXicoténcatl :bAn anonymous historical novel about the events leading up to the conquest of the Aztec empire /ced. by Guillermo Castillo-Feliú. 1aAustin : bUniversity of Texas Press, c[2021] 4c©1999  a1 online resource  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tTranslator's Note -- tIntroduction -- tBook One -- tBook Two -- tHook Three -- tBook Four -- tBook Five -- tBook Six0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aAs Spain's New World colonies fought for their independence in the early nineteenth century, an anonymous author looked back on the earlier struggle of native Americans against the Spanish conquistadores and penned this novel, Xicoténcatl. Writing from a decidedly anti-Spanish perspective, the author describes the historical events that led to the march on Tenochtitlán and eventual conquest of the Aztec empire in 1519 by Hernán Cortés and his Indian allies, the Tlaxcalans. Xicoténcatl stands out as a beautiful exposition of an idealized New World about to undergo the tremendous changes wrought by the Spanish Conquest. It was published in Philadelphia in 1826. In his introduction to this first English translation, Guillermo I. Castillo-Feliú discusses why the novel was published outside Latin America, its probable author, and his attitudes toward his Spanish and Indian characters, his debt to Spanish literature and culture, and the parallels that he draws between past and present struggles against Spanish domination in the Americas.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Nov 2021) 0aCortés, Hernán,-1485-1547-Fiction. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / General.2bisacsh1 aCastillo-Feliú, Guillermo, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt40uhttps://doi.org/10.7560/71213340uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780292753259423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780292753259/original  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_LT  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_LT  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK